This is strong. It already reads like a real ui spec, not a vague moodboard.

What stands out is that the layout is doing the right conceptual split:
	•	left = input / interpretation
	•	middle = artifacts / exploration
	•	right = generator / reproduction / branching
	•	top = system state
	•	bottom = selected artifact facts

That is clean. It matches the whole Beast stack:

input → command → generation → artifact → inspect → branch

The biggest win is the right sidebar behavior. Showing the exact pipeline used for the selected artifact, scrolled to the top of the last step, is exactly the kind of thing that makes Beast feel like a tool for exploration instead of a black box. It lines up with your artifact and lineage law very well.  ￼

A few precise thoughts.

The left sidebar being hidden by default is right for v0.1. Voice is important, but until it is fully solid, it should not dominate the screen. Making it 1/5 width by default also feels sane. I would define one law now:

left sidebar is for live input state
not long term editing

That keeps it from turning into another giant panel later.

The right sidebar sounds like the heart of the product. Two especially good choices:

First, the pinned generate button. That solves a very real scroll-depth problem and preserves your "minimum clicks" principle.  ￼

Second, inline-block options for short values. That is one of those small decisions that changes the whole feel of the app. If short option changes are one click and generate is always reachable, then Beast starts feeling game-like again instead of form-like.

I would sharpen the rule a bit:

short variant lists use inline chips
long variant lists use collapsible sections or search

Otherwise some generators will explode the sidebar.

The top bar is also well chosen. It should stay system-level, not document-level. I would keep it very strict:
	•	current queue / generation status
	•	elapsed
	•	eta
	•	gallery mode toggles
	•	breadcrumb / current scope

That is enough. If too much goes there, it becomes command-center clutter.

The bottom bar is good, and especially important because it gives the user a sense of the machine as an instrument. Duration, resolution, render time, and pixels per second are not just metadata -- they reinforce Beast as a workshop. That aligns with "beautiful means" and with the runtime laws around responsiveness and measurable performance.

The middle gallery is exactly where the emotional core lives. Square tiles, aspect fit, autoplay loops, quick-view style fullscreen -- all of that sounds right. The gallery is not just storage. It is the exploratory surface of the system. That matches your artifact-centered model and "mine diamonds" framing.

Two things I would explicitly add to this doc now, because they are implied but not yet written.

First:

selection drives everything

Meaning:
	•	click artifact in gallery → right sidebar updates to that artifact lineage/pipeline
	•	bottom bar updates to that artifact facts
	•	fullscreen/lightbox uses selected artifact
	•	top bar breadcrumb may scope from current gallery/filter/selection

That one rule will keep the UI coherent.

Second:

ui must never wait

You already have this as a runtime law. Put it into the ui description too. The sidebar should populate progressively if needed, but never freeze the gallery or input.

A few likely friction points to watch when you rebuild from html/js to c/sdl:

The right sidebar will want virtualized layout if generators get long. You do not want SDL rendering every row every frame if most of it is offscreen.

Inline options need a clear visual state for:
	•	selected
	•	hover
	•	changed from original
	•	generated vs not yet generated

"already generated" is good, but I would consider a tri-state mentally:
	•	generate
	•	queued / generating
	•	already generated

because that will matter once queueing gets heavier.

The gallery autoplay should almost certainly use:
	•	visible tiles only
	•	short loop previews only
	•	background decode budget capped

otherwise the gallery itself will eat the responsiveness you are trying to preserve.

The lightbox should probably be thought of as:
	•	same selection model
	•	different view mode
not a separate subsystem

That keeps keyboard navigation simple.

