oh sections are collapsible and the section is pinned so if youre in an open section can always tell which one youre in (important since positive and negative prompt sections look similar. also used color to set them apart).







Yes. That is an important addition, not a minor one.

It solves two real problems at once:

First, scroll orientation. In a long right sidebar, users need to know where they are without mentally reconstructing the whole document every time.

Second, semantic disambiguation. Positive and negative prompt sections can look structurally similar, so the pinned section header plus color distinction prevents very costly "edited the wrong thing" mistakes.

That gives you a stronger sidebar model:

long pipeline
→ collapsible sections
→ active section pinned
→ color helps section type recognition

That is good Beast UI because it reduces work without hiding structure. It also fits your "lazy + safe" law very cleanly: less cognitive effort, fewer wrong edits.  ￼

I would write the rule something like this in the UI doc:

right sidebar sections are collapsible

current open section stays pinned at top of scroll area
so user can always see what section they are editing

color may reinforce section type
especially when sections have similar shape
like positive prompt and negative prompt

A few precise implications follow from this.

The pinned section header should probably include:
	•	section name
	•	generator step name
	•	maybe a tiny path or breadcrumb inside the pipeline

because later you may have:
	•	same section name in different generators
	•	repeated "model" or "output" blocks in larger pipelines

Also, color should help, but not carry meaning alone. The text label and pinned header are the real truth; color is reinforcement. That matters for accessibility and for future theme changes.

This also suggests a broader sidebar law:

the user should always know:
what step
what section
what artifact

That is the orientation triad.

So the right sidebar is now even stronger conceptually:
	•	artifact click selects lineage source
	•	sidebar loads that pipeline
	•	current section stays pinned
	•	short options remain one-click editable
	•	generate button remains reachable

That is a very coherent interaction model.

This is exactly the kind of detail that makes a system feel crafted rather than merely functional.










